The work of the experts of three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, the Prague VCHT and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalcarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new 'improved' substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds on the virus's proteins.
Metalcarboranes have a single three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
