Manage revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies vis-à-vis its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to adhere to “values” determined from above as they used to be, to impose on consumers products designed by the factory’s technicians.
Putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets to the place ... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences comes back regularly.
Demobilisation of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects managers.
This demobilisation seriously jeopardises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, in particular of research and development and, even more so, of economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI “requires a proactive approach and a forward-looking approach” from all stakeholders; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues totally constrain.
That is why we are calling for a managerial revolution to put employees at the centre of the company’s concerns on the same basis as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I fear not.
First of all, because I have seen that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do as a matter of priority ... which it has always done. - -
- Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – is growing in proportion to the magnitude of one’s own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by US “neurosciences” and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by research institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manipulate the “levers” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr, it strengthens leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, unsuites to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists in incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, the commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears to be a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions and their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Patternation Analysis adopt this view of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them in order to carry out their life plans.
By identifying and measuring these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management back "on the right".
They thus create a fertile ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
