In our world that is too focused on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and head doctor of the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Dusseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also contains something positive, a creator – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of the modification of consciousness awakened by the dream.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is in a state of awakening.
Oniroid consciousness occurs during trauma or in situations of extreme conditions such as patients with polyradicularopathy who are fully aware of motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that undermines his life, by his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of the world is taking place, but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in a situation which is intolerable in itself, an organisational capacity that is given to us, to us men, so as not to sink into the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
