75 per cent of working mothers had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially for younger women in the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study “Fertility and professional career of women in Spain”, carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the onset of couple living and the number of children, whether or not the woman is working and the type of job held.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, start a couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, postpone entry into life as a couple and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 for those working in the public sector. “These data show that women in stable employment have needed more time in their lives to get it, leading them to postpone union and child arrival.
Moreover, the type of employment exerted largely influences maternity, but less the date of start of living together,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
Education is another factor that widens the age gap between women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women in the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another discipline also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with middle or higher education reverse this programme and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Delgado.
