New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are reduced to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of repair.
Each claim is different, and the calculation of coin and labour time costs can be a long and complex job.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair of between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000, including coins and labour, may take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the help of the latest IT tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
For this reason, almost 100 per cent of experts use such systems.
Service providers and solutions for claims assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting information provided by manufacturers, and then processing it and offering it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other competing companies in the field of evaluation tools and the development of information on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
The work with the data provided by the manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velazquez, the commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous 15 years.
When a new car comes out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult task, because it is necessary to catalogue each thousand parts of the vehicle and to register its price.
In addition, a “smart” graphical image of each model can be created on which the different parts of a passenger car can be clicked.
If it is a model sold on a massive scale, the work can be ready in a week if the process moves very quickly.
If it is a low-sold car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information about the Porsche, but not the Ferraris or the Lamborghini.
For vehicles in use, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centres around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than 100 technicians (generally mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million annually to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to give them different uses and to offer a variety of products.
The most frequent application concerns repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing breaker parts or for calculating the market or residual value of a car.
The only company with a guide that provides information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not propose it in our country, but it does so in the United States.
Given the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get a sense of what kind of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard solution for disaster assessment, for experts.
It includes cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of parts, it takes into account the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the paint schedules.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is EUR 5.75, for customers who use it little, at most ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expertise, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the complete identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it left the assembly line, only thanks to its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle lenses, and AudaSubastas is a professional server on the Internet that bids on vehicles declared wrecked.
Its statistical service is very useful for identifying trends, performing geo-demographic analyses or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a specified brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many serious disasters have suffered for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to developing such tools.
It markets, among others, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the manufacturer’s official parts, prices and time.
Gt Motive is a company in the Einsa group, founded in 1971, as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, breakdowns or maintenance.
The GT Assessment Guide is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased at a rate of 20% per year over the last three years, and it has made a turnover of EUR 10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its internationalisation process, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and established itself in Spain in 1979.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its turnover is in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. It works with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 garages, of which 3,000 are in Spain.
The global turnover of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex AB, Hollander and IMS) will amount to USD 557 million, 3.3% more than in 2008.
In our country, the company will receive EUR 19.1 million, or 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was publicly traded in the stock exchange of USD 1,000 million, and its shares are valued at a total of USD 2,400 million.
Since 2007, it has been on the New York Stock Exchange and is part of the Standard and Poor's benchmark.
Internet auctions of damaged cars
Last October, the Solera Group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of cars, motorcycles and disaster-stricken special vehicles.
The operation involved a cost of EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be extended next year to the remaining 15%.
The aim of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This estimation and sales service is intended exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, breaks and professional sellers who must be registered before starting to carry out operations.
The platform was established in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, including 500 000 in Germany.
Its main markets include Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently more than 1500 vendors and 4000 registered experts on the site.
It manages 3,000 advertisements per day and on the Spanish market, 100 new advertisements are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been removed may no longer circulate, but on the other hand, certain parts which are not damaged may be used as spare parts.
Collecting cars can be re-registered, even though they have been removed, after complex steps.
Garage quotation in four steps
With the Auda-Taller tool, the Audatex company ensures that the user obtains a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, search for the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
Ease of use is an essential element of these systems, especially in order to convince older professionals who, to a greater or lesser extent, are resistant to the use of new management techniques.
The database consists of 1,034 vehicles, including 666 passenger vehicles, 109 off-road, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Naturally, for use, a computer and an Internet connection are needed.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and then the necessary part is selected.
The user may include variables such as labour force price, mark-ups or discounts, and then he can print the quotation to hand it over to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a catalogue of references.
The main difference between these two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated labour times.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is EUR 350 per year, which can be credited.
Currently, Audatex is working to ensure that these images are in three dimensions.
This is an innovation that mechanics see very positively, since it will make it possible, for example, to select a door and rotate it to see the inner face.
